n-queens puzzle
The n-queens puzzle is the problem of placing n queens on an n x n chessboard such that no two queens attack each other.
Given an integer n, return all distinct solutions to the n-queens puzzle. You may return the answer in any order.
Each solution contains a distinct board configuration of the n-queens' placement, where 'Q' and '.' both indicate a queen and an empty space, respectively.

Input: n = 4
Output: [[".Q..","...Q","Q...","..Q."],["..Q.","Q...","...Q",".Q.."]]
Explanation: There exist two distinct solutions to the 4-queens puzzle as shown above
Example 2:

Input: n = 1
Output: [["Q"]]

class Solution {
    public List<List<String>> solveNQueens(int n) {
        List<List<String>> result=new ArrayList<>();
        char[][] board=new char[n][n];  
        for(char[] arr:board){
        Arrays.fill(arr,'.');
       }
       backtracking(0, new HashSet<>() ,new HashSet<>(),new HashSet<>(),board,result);
       return result;
    }
    public void backtracking(int row, HashSet<Integer> colSet,HashSet<Integer> diaSet,HashSet<Integer> AntiDiaSet,
    char [][] board,List<List<String>> result )   {
        if(row==board.length){
            List<String> newBoard=new ArrayList<>();
            for(char[] ch:board){
                newBoard.add(new String(ch));
            }
        result.add(new ArrayList<>(newBoard));
        return;
        }
        
        for(int col=0;col<board.length;col++){
            if(colSet.contains(col)||
            diaSet.contains(row-col)||
            AntiDiaSet.contains(row+col)){
                continue;
            }
            board[row][col]='Q';
            colSet.add(col);
            diaSet.add(row-col);
            AntiDiaSet.add(row+col);
            backtracking(row+1,colSet,diaSet,AntiDiaSet,board,result);
            colSet.remove(col);
            diaSet.remove(row-col);
            AntiDiaSet.remove(row+col);
            board[row][col]='.';
            
        }
    }
}
Time Complexity = O(n!)

Space Complexity:
Space Complexity = O(n^2)
 
